        <!-- required; can be short -->
        <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
            <head>Biographical Note</head>

            <p>Fanto was born in Budapest, Hungary on August 4, 1911. He was a cinematographer who
                photographed what became Welles's unfinished documentary on Latin America, <title
                    render="italic">It's All True;</title> followed by Welles's screen adaptation of
                    <title render="italic">Othello</title> (released in Europe in 1952 and the
                United States in 1955).</p>
        </bioghist>
        <!--optional -->
        <arrangement encodinganalog="351">
            <head>Arrangement</head>
            <p>Arranged in the following series: I. Correspondence, II. Script materials, III.
                Miscellaneous, IV. Photographs, V. Clippings. </p>
        </arrangement>

        <!-- required for collection level; optional for lower levels -->
        <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">

            <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
            <p> Fanto first worked with Welles in Brazil in 1941. The majority of the materials in
                the collection are from 1949-1950 during the filming of Othello in Europe and North
                Africa. Most of the letters in the collection are from Welles to Fanto. Other items
                include a partial script, shooting instructions and financial materials for Othello,
                a script for the play Time Runs, a partial script for the proposed film Twice Is Too
                Much, a playbill for the Unthinking Lobster and Time Runs, and a synopsis of a
                proposed film Life Is a Song. The photographs include a portrait of Welles and
                photographs taken during the filming of It's All True and Othello. </p>
        </scopecontent>

